> show that the size of the polyp (arrowhead) is preserved without producing cleansing artifacts.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170173&amp;id=fig13e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170173/asset/images/large/rg.2018170173.fig13f.jpeg" height="1100" width="1361" aria-labelledby="fig13f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13f</span>. Electronic cleansing of semi-solid tagged feces with a submerged 6-mm polyp. <b>(a)</b> The uncleansed axial CT colonographic image shows the polyp (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> The virtual endoluminal view shows how the semisolid feces obstruct the view of the polyp. <b>(c, d)</b> After cleansing with a conventional EC method, the axial CT colonographic image <b>(c)</b> and virtual endoluminal view <b>(d)</b> show the distorted shape of the polyp (arrowhead). <b>(e, f)</b> After cleansing with the deep learning single-energy EC scheme, the axial CT colonographic image <b>(e)</b> and virtual endoluminal view <b>(f)</b> reveal the polyp (arrowhead), but the polyp appears inaccurately smaller. <b>(g, h)</b> After cleansing with the deep learning dual-energy EC scheme, axial CT colonographic image <b>(g)</b> and virtual endoluminal view <b>(h)</b> show that the size of the polyp (arrowhead) is preserved without producing cleansing artifacts.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170173&amp;id=fig13f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13g" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170173/asset/images/large/rg.2018170173.fig13g.jpeg" height="1103" width="1092" aria-labelledby="fig13g" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="hea